revision.text:
'''Sawtooth Pattern''' (鋸歯文, Kyoshimon) is a type of {{ill|geometric pattern|ja|幾何学文様|12=draft|12=draft}} characterized by a series of interconnected triangles. The name derives from its resemblance to the teeth of a saw.<ref name=sakadume>{{Cite book|author=Sakazume, Shuichi|title=Sawtooth Pattern|work={{ill|Kokushi Daijiten (Showa Era)|ja|国史大辞典 (昭和時代)|12=draft|12=draft}} Vol. 4|publisher={{ill|Yoshikawa Kobunkan|ja|吉川弘文館|12=draft|12=draft}}|year=1984|isbn=978-4-642-00504-3}}</ref><ref name=kanou>{{Cite book|author=Kanou, Shunsuke|title=Sawtooth Pattern|work={{ill|Nihon Rekishi Daijiten|ja|日本歴史大事典|12=draft|12=draft}} Vol. 1|publisher=Shogakukan|year=2000|isbn=978-4-095-23001-6}}</ref>
This pattern is observed on {{ill|Han dynasty|ja|漢|12=draft|12=draft}} {{ill|bronze vessels|ja|青銅器|12=draft|12=draft}} in {{ill|China|ja|中国|12=draft|12=draft}}, suggesting it may have been introduced to Japan from China.<ref name=sakadume/> However, some scholars argue it already existed during the {{ill|Jōmon period|ja|縄文時代|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref name=kanou/>
From the {{ill|Yayoi period|ja|弥生時代|12=draft|12=draft}} onward, the sawtooth pattern was widely applied to various cultural artifacts, such as {{ill|Yayoi pottery|ja|弥生土器|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|dotaku|ja|銅鐸|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|bronze mirrors|ja|銅鏡|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|haniwa|ja|埴輪|12=draft|12=draft}}, tiles, and the wall decorations of {{ill|kofun|ja|古墳|1=Kofun|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref name=sakadume/><ref name=kanou/> Additionally, some variations of the sawtooth pattern include parallel lines engraved within the design or added coloration.<ref name=sakadume/><ref name=kanou/>
== References == <references/>
== Bibliography == * Sakazume, Shuichi. "Sawtooth Pattern." In *{{ill|Kokushi Daijiten (Showa Era)|ja|国史大辞典 (昭和時代)|12=draft|12=draft}}* Vol. 4, {{ill|Yoshikawa Kobunkan|ja|吉川弘文館|12=draft|12=draft}}, 1984. ISBN 978-4-642-00504-3. * Kanou, Shunsuke. "Sawtooth Pattern." In *{{ill|Nihon Rekishi Daijiten|ja|日本歴史大事典|12=draft|12=draft}}* Vol. 1, Shogakukan, 2000. ISBN 978-4-095-23001-6.
