'''Sawtooth Pattern''' (鋸歯文, Kyoshimon) is a type of {{ill|geometric pattern|ja|幾何学文様|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/geometric pattern|qq=}} characterized by a series of interconnected triangles. The name derives from its resemblance to the teeth of a saw.<ref name=sakadume>{{Cite book|author=Sakazume, Shuichi|title=Sawtooth Pattern|work=[[:en:Kokushi Daijiten|Kokushi Daijiten (Showa Era)]] Vol. 4|publisher={{ill|Yoshikawa Kobunkan|ja|吉川弘文館|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoshikawa Kobunkan|qq=}}|year=1984|isbn=978-4-642-00504-3}}</ref><ref name=kanou>{{Cite book|author=Kanou, Shunsuke|title=Sawtooth Pattern|work={{ill|Nihon Rekishi Daijiten|ja|日本歴史大事典|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nihon Rekishi Daijiten|qq=}} Vol. 1|publisher=Shogakukan|year=2000|isbn=978-4-095-23001-6}}</ref>
This pattern is observed on [[:en:Han dynasty|Han dynasty]] {{ill|bronze vessels|ja|青銅器|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/bronze vessels|qq=}} in {{ill|China|ja|中国|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/China|qq=}}, suggesting it may have been introduced to Japan from China.<ref name=sakadume/> However, some scholars argue it already existed during the [[:en:Jōmon period|Jōmon period]].<ref name=kanou/>
From the [[:en:Yayoi period|Yayoi period]] onward, the sawtooth pattern was widely applied to various cultural artifacts, such as [[:en:Yayoi pottery|Yayoi pottery]], [[:en:Dōtaku|dotaku]], [[:en:Bronze mirror|bronze mirrors]], [[:en:Haniwa|haniwa]], tiles, and the wall decorations of [[:en:Kofun|Kofun]].<ref name=sakadume/><ref name=kanou/> Additionally, some variations of the sawtooth pattern include parallel lines engraved within the design or added coloration.<ref name=sakadume/><ref name=kanou/>
